mains of the Borscht Belt era now lie forgotten, overgrown, and vacant. In the absence of human activity, nature has reclaimed the sites, having encroached upon or completely overtaken them. Many of the interiors have been vandalized or marked by paintball players and graffiti artists. Each ruin lies radically altered by the elements and effects of time. Scheinfeld’s images record all of these developments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAbandoned buildingszNew York (State)zCatskill Mountains RegionvPictorial works. 0aCatskill Mountain Region (N.Y.). 0aJewszNew York (State)zCatskill Mountains RegionxSocial life and customs. 0aResortszNew York (State)zCatskill Mountains RegionvPictorial works. 4aArt History. 4aPhotography.1 aJoselit, Jenna Weissman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanfer, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScheinfeld, Marisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150170771140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501707711423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501707711/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles